<subSubSection id="4FF0F1E8FF7FFF35A7ADF9D5FC81DB35" pageId="230" pageNumber="231" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="0755A263FF7FFF35A7ADF9D5FEF0DA55" blockId="230.[189,310,1594,1620]" box="[189,310,1594,1620]" pageId="230" pageNumber="231">
<heading id="5C1D150FFF7FFF35A7ADF9D5FEF0DA55" bold="true" box="[189,310,1594,1620]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="230" pageNumber="231" reason="3">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF7FFF35A7ADF9D5FEF0DA55" bold="true" box="[189,310,1594,1620]" pageId="230" pageNumber="231">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0755A263FF7FFF35A7ADF986FC81DB35" blockId="230.[189,1400,1641,1844]" pageId="230" pageNumber="231">
Based on 
<bibRefCitation id="637BDF92FF7FFF35A63FF986FD6BDA85" author="Weygoldt P. &amp; Van Damme K." box="[303,685,1641,1668]" firstAuthor="Weygoldt" journalOrPublisher="Fauna of Arabia" pageId="230" pageNumber="231" pagination="327 - 334" part="20" refId="ref156483" refString="Weygoldt P. &amp; Van Damme K. 2004. A new troglomorphic whip spider of the genus Charinus (Amblypygi: Charinidae) from Socotra Island. Fauna of Arabia 20: 327 - 334." title="A new troglomorphic whip spider of the genus Charinus (Amblypygi: Charinidae) from Socotra Island" type="journal article" year="2004">
Weygoldt &amp; 
<collectingRegion id="C52E6C81FF7FFF35A6D5F985FE35DA85" box="[453,499,1642,1668]" country="Turkey" name="Van" pageId="230" pageNumber="231">Van</collectingRegion>
Damme (2004)
</bibRefCitation>
, this small species resembles 
<taxonomicName id="C0EAD9E0FF7FFF35A318F985FB61DA82" authorityName="Miranda &amp; Giupponi &amp; Prendini &amp; Scharff" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Weygoldt, Pohl &amp; Polak" baseAuthorityYear="2002" box="[1032,1191,1642,1668]" class="Arachnida" family="Charinidae" genus="Sarax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amblypygi" pageId="230" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="socotranus" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF7FFF35A318F985FB61DA82" box="[1032,1191,1642,1668]" italics="true" pageId="230" pageNumber="231">S. socotranus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="2EADC30AFF7FFF35A3BDF986FAE8DA85" box="[1197,1326,1641,1668]" pageId="230" pageNumber="231" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in the similar genitalia, the leg basitibia with only two articles, and the similar arrangement of trichobothria on leg IV. It differs from 
<taxonomicName id="C0EAD9E0FF7FFF35A6FDF95EFD4BDACB" authorityName="Miranda &amp; Giupponi &amp; Prendini &amp; Scharff" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Weygoldt, Pohl &amp; Polak" baseAuthorityYear="2002" box="[493,653,1713,1739]" class="Arachnida" family="Charinidae" genus="Sarax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amblypygi" pageId="230" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="socotranus" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF7FFF35A6FDF95EFD4BDACB" box="[493,653,1713,1739]" italics="true" pageId="230" pageNumber="231">S. socotranus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="2EADC30AFF7FFF35A586F95FFCDFDACA" box="[662,793,1712,1739]" pageId="230" pageNumber="231" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in the extreme level of troglomorphism, including complete loss of eyes (
<figureCitation id="9FD1BEE6FF7FFF35A6C8F93CFDBADAEF" box="[472,636,1747,1774]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="404.[189,231,1611,1637]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,1578]" captionTargetId="figure-51@404.[189,1399,265,1578]" captionTargetPageId="404" captionText="Fig. 149. Sarax stygochthobius(Weygoldt &amp;Van Damme, 2004) comb.nov.(HLMD EA–172–HT), general morphology, ♂. A. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Sternum, ventral view. C. Frontal process. D. Pedipalp, dorsal view. F. Pedipalp, ventral view. Scale bars: A–B, D–E = 1 mm; C = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5536827" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5536827/files/figure.png" pageId="230" pageNumber="231">Fig. 149A, C</figureCitation>
), elongate legs and structures such as the trochanter apophysis (
<figureCitation id="9FD1BEE6FF7FFF35A7D6F918FEA2DB10" box="[198,356,1783,1809]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="404.[189,231,1611,1637]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,1578]" captionTargetId="figure-51@404.[189,1399,265,1578]" captionTargetPageId="404" captionText="Fig. 149. Sarax stygochthobius(Weygoldt &amp;Van Damme, 2004) comb.nov.(HLMD EA–172–HT), general morphology, ♂. A. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Sternum, ventral view. C. Frontal process. D. Pedipalp, dorsal view. F. Pedipalp, ventral view. Scale bars: A–B, D–E = 1 mm; C = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5536827" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5536827/files/figure.png" pageId="230" pageNumber="231">Fig. 149A, E</figureCitation>
). The sternum setation is typical (
<figureCitation id="9FD1BEE6FF7FFF35A5E6F918FCB7DB10" box="[758,881,1783,1809]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="404.[189,231,1611,1637]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,1578]" captionTargetId="figure-51@404.[189,1399,265,1578]" captionTargetPageId="404" captionText="Fig. 149. Sarax stygochthobius(Weygoldt &amp;Van Damme, 2004) comb.nov.(HLMD EA–172–HT), general morphology, ♂. A. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Sternum, ventral view. C. Frontal process. D. Pedipalp, dorsal view. F. Pedipalp, ventral view. Scale bars: A–B, D–E = 1 mm; C = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5536827" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5536827/files/figure.png" pageId="230" pageNumber="231">Fig. 149B</figureCitation>
). The pedipalps of preserved specimens are turned upwards, with the femora held almost vertically.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4FF0F1E8FF7FFF35A7ADF8B3FA82DBE9" pageId="230" pageNumber="231" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="0755A263FF7FFF35A7ADF8B3FE82DB77" blockId="230.[189,324,1884,1910]" box="[189,324,1884,1910]" pageId="230" pageNumber="231">
<heading id="5C1D150FFF7FFF35A7ADF8B3FE82DB77" bold="true" box="[189,324,1884,1910]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="230" pageNumber="231" reason="3">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF7FFF35A7ADF8B3FE82DB77" bold="true" box="[189,324,1884,1910]" pageId="230" pageNumber="231">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0755A263FF7FFF35A7ADF866FA82DBE9" blockId="230.[189,1398,1929,2025]" pageId="230" pageNumber="231">
The species name is combination of the Greek words ‘ 
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF7FFF35A45FF865FC4BDBA2" box="[847,909,1930,1955]" italics="true" pageId="230" pageNumber="231">stygo</emphasis>
’, referring to the Styx, the main river of the underworld, according to the Greek mythology, ‘ 
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF7FFF35A437F843FCB3DBC7" box="[807,885,1964,1990]" italics="true" pageId="230" pageNumber="231">ochthy</emphasis>
’, meaning ‘riverbank’, and ‘ 
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF7FFF35A3D8F843FB3FDBC7" box="[1224,1273,1964,1990]" italics="true" pageId="230" pageNumber="231">bios</emphasis>
’, meaning ‘life’, all together meaning ‘living on the banks of the river Styx’ (
<bibRefCitation id="637BDF92FF7FFF35A4D6F821FAF1DBE9" author="Weygoldt P. &amp; Van Damme K." box="[966,1335,1998,2025]" firstAuthor="Weygoldt" journalOrPublisher="Fauna of Arabia" pageId="230" pageNumber="231" pagination="327 - 334" part="20" refId="ref156483" refString="Weygoldt P. &amp; Van Damme K. 2004. A new troglomorphic whip spider of the genus Charinus (Amblypygi: Charinidae) from Socotra Island. Fauna of Arabia 20: 327 - 334." title="A new troglomorphic whip spider of the genus Charinus (Amblypygi: Charinidae) from Socotra Island" type="journal article" year="2004">
Weygoldt &amp; 
